    {
      "content": "Troubleshooting DSC",
      "pos": [
        2,
        21
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Applies To: Windows PowerShell 4.0, Windows PowerShell 5.0",
      "pos": [
        24,
        82
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This topic describes methods for getting your Desired State Configuration (DSC) scripts to run without error.",
      "pos": [
        84,
        193
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By using logs effectively to track down errors, and understanding how to recycle the cache to see the immediate results of your resource changes, you’ll be able to troubleshoot DSC more effectively.",
      "pos": [
        194,
        392
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These technics are discussed in two sections:",
      "pos": [
        393,
        438
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        442,
        507
      ],
      "content": "My script won’t run: <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Using DSC logs to diagnose script errors<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        510,
        563
      ],
      "content": "My resources won’t update: <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>How to reset the cache<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>"
    },
    {
      "content": "My script won’t run: Using DSC logs to diagnose script errors",
      "pos": [
        568,
        629
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Like all Windows software, DSC records errors and events in <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>logs<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/aa363632.aspx)</ept> that can be viewed from the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Event Viewer<ept id=\"p2\">](http://windows.microsoft.com/windows/what-information-event-logs-event-viewer)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        631,
        886
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Examining these logs can help you understand why a particular operation failed, and how to prevent failure in the future.",
      "pos": [
        887,
        1008
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Writing configuration scripts can be tricky, so to make tracking errors easier as you author, use the DSC Log resource to track the progress of your configuration in the DSC Analytic event log.",
      "pos": [
        1009,
        1202
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Where are DSC event logs?",
      "pos": [
        1207,
        1232
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        1234,
        1350
      ],
      "content": "In Event Viewer, DSC events are in: <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Applications and Services Logs/Microsoft/Windows/Desired State Configuration<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        1352,
        1497
      ],
      "content": "The corresponding PowerShell cmdlet, <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Get-WinEvent<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/hh849682.aspx)</ept>, can also be run to view the event logs:"
    },
    {
      "content": "As shown above, DSC’s primary log name is <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Microsoft-&gt;Windows-&gt;DSC<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> (other log names under Windows are not shown here for brevity).",
      "pos": [
        2027,
        2160
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The primary name is appended to the channel name to create the complete log name.",
      "pos": [
        2161,
        2242
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The DSC engine writes mainly into three types of logs: <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Operational, Analytic, and Debug logs<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/cc722404.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        2243,
        2391
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Since the analytic and debug logs are turned off by default, you should enable them in Event Viewer.",
      "pos": [
        2392,
        2492
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To do this, open Event Viewer by typing Show-EventLog in Windows PowerShell; or, click the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Start<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> button, click <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Control Panel<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>, click <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Administrative Tools<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept>, and then click <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>Event Viewer<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        2493,
        2691
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>View<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> menu in Event viewer, click <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Show Analytic and Debug Logs<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        2692,
        2769
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The log name for the analytic channel is <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Microsoft-Windows-Dsc/Analytic<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, and the debug channel is <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Microsoft-Windows-Dsc/Debug<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        2770,
        2904
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You could also use the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>wevtutil<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/cc732848.aspx)</ept> utility to enable the logs, as shown in the following example.",
      "pos": [
        2905,
        3054
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "What do DSC logs contain?",
      "pos": [
        3148,
        3173
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "DSC logs are split over the three log channels based on the importance of the message.",
      "pos": [
        3175,
        3261
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The operational log in DSC contains all error messages, and can be used to identify a problem.",
      "pos": [
        3262,
        3356
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The analytic log has a higher volume of events, and can identify where error(s) occurred.",
      "pos": [
        3357,
        3446
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This channel also contains verbose messages (if any).",
      "pos": [
        3447,
        3500
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The debug log contains logs that can help you understand how the errors occurred.",
      "pos": [
        3501,
        3582
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "DSC event messages are structured such that every event message begins with a job ID that uniquely represents a DSC operation.",
      "pos": [
        3583,
        3709
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The example below attempts to obtain the message from the first event logged into the operational DSC log.",
      "pos": [
        3710,
        3816
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "DSC events are logged in a particular structure that enables the user to aggregate events from one DSC job.",
      "pos": [
        4100,
        4207
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The structure is as follows:",
      "pos": [
        4208,
        4236
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Job ID : <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;Guid&gt;</ph><ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>",
      "pos": [
        4238,
        4257
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Gathering events from a single DSC operation",
      "pos": [
        4282,
        4326
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "DSC event logs contain events generated by various DSC operations.",
      "pos": [
        4328,
        4394
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, you’ll usually be concerned with the detail about just one particular operation.",
      "pos": [
        4395,
        4484
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "All DSC logs can be grouped by the job ID property that is unique for every DSC operation.",
      "pos": [
        4485,
        4575
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The job ID is displayed as the first property value in all DSC events.",
      "pos": [
        4576,
        4646
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following steps explain how to accumulate all events in a grouped array structure.",
      "pos": [
        4647,
        4733
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Here, the variable <ph id=\"ph1\">`$SeparateDscOperations`</ph> contains logs grouped by the job IDs.",
      "pos": [
        6187,
        6268
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Each array element of this variable represents a group of events logged by a different DSC operation, allowing access to more information about the logs.",
      "pos": [
        6269,
        6422
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can extract the data in the variable <ph id=\"ph1\">`$SeparateDscOperations`</ph> using <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Where-Object<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/ee177028.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8793,
        8933
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Following are five scenarios in which you might want to extract data for troubleshooting DSC:",
      "pos": [
        8934,
        9027
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "1: Operations failures",
      "pos": [
        9033,
        9055
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "All events have <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>severity levels<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/dd996917(v=vs.85))</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        9057,
        9145
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This information can be used to identify the error events:",
      "pos": [
        9146,
        9204
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "2: Details of operations run in the last half hour",
      "pos": [
        9632,
        9682
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">`TimeCreated`</ph>, a property of every Windows event, states the time the event was created.",
      "pos": [
        9684,
        9772
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Comparing this property with a particular date/time object can be used to filter all events:",
      "pos": [
        9773,
        9865
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "3: Messages from the latest operation",
      "pos": [
        10325,
        10362
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The latest operation is stored in the first index of the array group <ph id=\"ph1\">`$SeparateDscOperations`</ph>.",
      "pos": [
        10364,
        10458
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Querying the group’s messages for index 0 returns all messages for the latest operation:",
      "pos": [
        10459,
        10547
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "4: Error messages logged for recent failed operations",
      "pos": [
        11219,
        11272
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">`$SeparateDscOperations[0].Group`</ph> contains a set of events for the latest operation.",
      "pos": [
        11274,
        11358
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Run the <ph id=\"ph1\">`Where-Object`</ph> cmdlet to filter the events based on their level display name.",
      "pos": [
        11359,
        11444
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Results are stored in the <ph id=\"ph1\">`$myFailedEvent`</ph> variable, which can be further dissected to get the event message:",
      "pos": [
        11445,
        11554
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "5: All events generated for a particular job ID.",
      "pos": [
        11991,
        12039
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">`$SeparateDscOperations`</ph> is an array of groups, each of which has the name as the unique job ID.",
      "pos": [
        12041,
        12137
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By running the <ph id=\"ph1\">`Where-Object`</ph> cmdlet, you can extract those groups of events that have a particular job ID:",
      "pos": [
        12138,
        12245
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Using xDscDiagnostics to analyze DSC logs",
      "pos": [
        13024,
        13065
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>xDscDiagnostics<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> is a PowerShell module that consists of two simple functions that can help analyze DSC failures on your machine: <ph id=\"ph1\">`Get-xDscOperation`</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">`Trace-xDscOperation`</ph>.",
      "pos": [
        13067,
        13246
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These functions can help you identify all local events from past DSC operations, or DSC events on remote computers (with valid credentials).",
      "pos": [
        13247,
        13387
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Here, the term DSC operation is used to define a single unique DSC execution from its start to its end.",
      "pos": [
        13388,
        13491
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, <ph id=\"ph1\">`Test-DscConfiguration`</ph> would be a separate DSC operation.",
      "pos": [
        13492,
        13563
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Similarly, every other cmdlet in DSC (such as <ph id=\"ph1\">`Get-DscConfiguration`</ph>, <ph id=\"ph2\">`Start-DscConfiguration`</ph>, etc.) could each be identified as separate DSC operations.",
      "pos": [
        13564,
        13718
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The two functions are explained in <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>xDscDiagnostics<ept id=\"p1\">](https://powershellgallery.com/packages/xDscDiagnostics)</ept> PowerShell Module (DSC Resource Kit) and in more detail below.",
      "pos": [
        13719,
        13890
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Help is available by running <ph id=\"ph1\">`Get-Help &lt;cmdlet name&gt;`</ph>.",
      "pos": [
        13891,
        13945
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Get-xDscOperation",
      "pos": [
        13950,
        13967
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This function lets you find the results of the DSC operations that run on one or multiple computers, and returns an object that contains the collection of events produced by each DSC operation.",
      "pos": [
        13969,
        14162
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, in the following output, three commands were run.",
      "pos": [
        14163,
        14225
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The first one passed, and the other two failed.",
      "pos": [
        14226,
        14273
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These results are summarized in the output of <ph id=\"ph1\">`Get-xDscOperation`</ph>.",
      "pos": [
        14274,
        14340
      ]
    },
